abstract={Our present understanding of the structure of the Hoyle state in {\$}{\$}^{\{}12{\}}{\$}{\$}C and other near-threshold states in {\$}{\$}{\backslash}alpha {\$}{\$}-conjugate nuclei is reviewed in the framework of the {\$}{\$}{\backslash}alpha {\$}{\$}-condensate model. The {\$}{\$}^{\{}12{\}}{\$}{\$}C Hoyle state, in particular, is a candidate for {\$}{\$}{\backslash}alpha {\$}{\$}-condensation, due to its large radius and {\$}{\$}{\backslash}alpha {\$}{\$}-cluster structure. The predicted features of nuclear {\$}{\$}{\backslash}alpha {\$}{\$}-particle condensates are reviewed along with a discussion of their experimental indicators, with a focus on precision break-up measurements. Two experiments are discussed in detail, firstly concerning the break-up of {\$}{\$}^{\{}12{\}}{\$}{\$}C and then the decays of heavier nuclei. With more theoretical input, and increasingly complex detector setups, precision break-up measurements can, in principle, provide insight into the structures of states in {\$}{\$}{\backslash}alpha {\$}{\$}-conjugate nuclei. However, the commonly-held belief that the decay of a condensate state will result in N{\$}{\$}{\backslash}alpha {\$}{\$}-particles is challenged. We further conclude that unambiguously characterising excited states built on {\$}{\$}{\backslash}alpha {\$}{\$}-condensates is difficult, despite improvements in detector technology.},
